00:55:03.870 --> 00:55:04.700
before I came in.

00:55:04.700 --> 00:55:08.800
There's some thumping on that
side that I'm hearing on the

00:55:08.800 --> 00:55:11.680
192 which I don't really
hear in the MP3.

00:55:11.680 --> 00:55:13.840
So you don't always--

00:55:13.840 --> 00:55:15.410
like, oh my god, it's
just so much better.

00:55:15.410 --> 00:55:17.840
Sometimes you uncover other
things along the way.

00:55:17.840 --> 00:55:21.620
AUDIENCE: Do you have a
non-YouTube [INAUDIBLE]

00:55:21.620 --> 00:55:22.440
ANDREW SCHEPS: Yeah.

00:55:22.440 --> 00:55:24.350
We can do--

00:55:24.350 --> 00:55:28.010
well, your stuff would be 320.

00:55:28.010 --> 00:55:31.000
So we could do 320, or
we could do Amazon if

00:55:31.000 --> 00:55:32.230
you want to do that.

00:55:32.230 --> 00:55:35.120
Let's do Amazon.

00:55:35.120 --> 00:55:37.380
Well, I just told you,
it's Amazon.

00:55:37.380 --> 00:55:38.230
I'll leave it up.

00:55:38.230 --> 00:55:39.800
OK, but here's Amazon.

00:55:39.800 --> 00:55:42.000
AUDIENCE: Can you do it, and
then we vote which is which?

00:55:42.000 --> 00:55:44.110
ANDREW SCHEPS: Yeah.

00:55:44.110 --> 00:55:44.440
Yeah.

00:55:44.440 --> 00:55:46.180
Let me just play you some of
the Amazon of the Coltrane,

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:48.070
and then we'll go to a different
song, and I won't

00:55:48.070 --> 00:55:50.110
say a word.

00:55:50.110 --> 00:55:54.090
Now I'm crazy, so I did some
FFTs of some of this stuff.

00:55:54.090 --> 00:55:57.040
And one of the things that
Amazon does-- because they're

00:55:57.040 --> 00:56:00.640
only selling 256 MP3s, that's
what they sell--

00:56:00.640 --> 00:56:03.770
and presumably to help
their encoder--

00:56:03.770 --> 00:56:06.100
because they're not getting
24-bit files, either--

00:56:06.100 --> 00:56:09.670
they actually pretty much cut
off everything above 15k.

00:56:09.670 --> 00:56:13.220
So that's ban limited to 15k on
the way into the encoder,

00:56:13.220 --> 00:56:17.600
because if you don't have to
bother encoding from 15 to 20,

00:56:17.600 --> 00:56:21.050
you've got that much more
room to encode below.

00:56:21.050 --> 00:56:23.460
So that's their decision.

00:56:23.460 --> 00:56:26.830
Again, now I'm right between
the speakers, so for me the

00:56:26.830 --> 00:56:28.640
imaging is a pretty
obvious thing.

00:56:28.640 --> 00:56:31.400
The 192 is the only one where
things are either on the left

00:56:31.400 --> 00:56:32.300
or in the right.

00:56:32.300 --> 00:56:35.080
And Rudy Van Gelder, who
recorded this album, did not

00:56:35.080 --> 00:56:36.020
have a pan pot.

00:56:36.020 --> 00:56:36.990
It was a patch cord.

00:56:36.990 --> 00:56:39.930
It was either in the left or
the right, and that's it.

00:56:39.930 --> 00:56:42.850
So as soon as you get anything
that isn't discretely on one

00:56:42.850 --> 00:56:45.730
side or the other, you know it's
part of the process of

00:56:45.730 --> 00:56:48.250
the encoding that has
made things shift.

00:56:48.250 --> 00:56:50.980
And that's another way that a
lot of the encoders work.

00:56:50.980 --> 00:56:53.520
And I don't know specifically
the ones you use because

00:56:53.520 --> 00:56:56.730
you're writing your own
encoders, if you mono up

00:56:56.730 --> 00:56:58.920
stuff, , it makes it much
easier to encode.

00:56:58.920 --> 00:57:00.160
It's one audio stream, and it's

00:57:00.160 --> 00:57:01.450
identical in both channels.

00:57:01.450 --> 00:57:03.610
So you can save a lot of space
doing it that way.

00:57:03.610 --> 00:57:07.340
And I'm sure that's part of the
pre-encoding of a lot of

00:57:07.340 --> 00:57:09.470
this stuff, especially at
the lower bit rates.

00:57:09.470 --> 00:57:10.500
So that'll happen.

00:57:10.500 --> 00:57:12.990
And it's not that big a deal
on modern pop stuff because

00:57:12.990 --> 00:57:15.390
stuff is everywhere, but any of
the Beatles stuff, all the

00:57:15.390 --> 00:57:18.850
old Motown stuff, the Blue
Note stuff, that is all

00:57:18.850 --> 00:57:21.160
discrete stereo, and it will
change it completely.

00:57:21.160 --> 00:57:23.560
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:57:23.560 --> 00:57:25.480
are you thinking about
[INAUDIBLE]

00:57:28.360 --> 00:57:29.620
ANDREW SCHEPS: No.

00:57:29.620 --> 00:57:31.740
No, I refuse to.

00:57:31.740 --> 00:57:37.060
So here's my theory, is that I
need to make my records sound

00:57:37.060 --> 00:57:39.860
as good as I can make them
sound regardless of what

00:57:39.860 --> 00:57:41.420
happens afterwards.

00:57:41.420 --> 00:57:44.980
So then, when I realized what
was happening afterwards, I

00:57:44.980 --> 00:57:48.580
asked the Recording Academy so
let me come and talk about it.

00:57:48.580 --> 00:57:50.830
And they said, sure, we've
been trying to figure--

00:57:50.830 --> 00:57:52.450
because they've had this
Quality Sound Matters

00:57:52.450 --> 00:57:55.620
initiative officially for a
little over a year, but

00:57:55.620 --> 00:57:57.200
unofficially for the
last 10 years.

00:57:57.200 --> 00:57:59.260
And they've had ideas about--

00:57:59.260 --> 00:58:02.273
we're going to get buses and put
awesome sound systems in

00:58:02.273 --> 00:58:04.090
them, and we're going to drive
them around and play this

00:58:04.090 --> 00:58:06.800
stuff for people, and trying
to come up with ways to let

00:58:06.800 --> 00:58:08.870
people here what the difference
is so that you can

00:58:08.870 --> 00:58:09.850
start to understand.

00:58:09.850 --> 00:58:13.290
So when I came up with this
presentation as a way to do

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:14.910
it, they were all over it
and have allowed me

00:58:14.910 --> 00:58:15.400
to come and do it.

00:58:15.400 --> 00:58:18.870
So my idea is to find
out what's actually

00:58:18.870 --> 00:58:20.620
important, and change it.

00:58:20.620 --> 00:58:23.670
I refuse to live with the crap,
and just say, I got to

00:58:23.670 --> 00:58:26.900
make it work on earbuds, because
in five years, it

00:58:26.900 --> 00:58:27.520
won't be earbuds.

00:58:27.520 --> 00:58:29.460
And the pipes will be bigger,
and you guys will flip a

00:58:29.460 --> 00:58:32.420
switch, and it's going to be
either uncompressed or barely

00:58:32.420 --> 00:58:32.960
compressed.

00:58:32.960 --> 00:58:36.580
And so now, I've changed my
whole workflow to cater to

00:58:36.580 --> 00:58:37.470
something that goes away.

00:58:37.470 --> 00:58:38.850
And it's one of--

00:58:38.850 --> 00:58:41.520
not to talk about your
neighbors-- but it's one of

00:58:41.520 --> 00:58:45.870
the biggest problems I have with
Apple conceptually, is

00:58:45.870 --> 00:58:49.350
that they will talk a lot about
what they want to get

00:58:49.350 --> 00:58:51.840
from the labels and from the
artists in terms of their

00:58:51.840 --> 00:58:53.590
ingestion, and they want
24 bit, and they

00:58:53.590 --> 00:58:55.340
want the high res.

00:58:55.340 --> 00:58:59.600
But if I master specifically for
their encoder right now,

00:58:59.600 --> 00:59:03.780
in three weeks, if they say,
bandwidth is awesome.

00:59:03.780 --> 00:59:05.590
We're going to start
selling 320 AACs.

00:59:05.590 --> 00:59:07.680
Well, now it's a new encoder,
or they just

00:59:07.680 --> 00:59:08.690
update their encoder.

00:59:08.690 --> 00:59:10.410
All of a sudden, I'm making
decisions based on

00:59:10.410 --> 00:59:11.900
things that go away.

00:59:11.900 --> 00:59:15.710
And I think it's a very big
difference between the record

00:59:15.710 --> 00:59:19.620
making process and the consumer
distribution world,

00:59:19.620 --> 00:59:23.300
and you can't make records for
the consumer distribution

00:59:23.300 --> 00:59:26.580
world other than a lot of the
analog limitations we used to

00:59:26.580 --> 00:59:27.120
have to deal with.

00:59:27.120 --> 00:59:30.170
Like you can't pan your bass off
to one side if there's a

00:59:30.170 --> 00:59:32.530
lot of low end, and
still cut vinyl.

00:59:32.530 --> 00:59:35.030
OK, like their physical
limitations to things which

00:59:35.030 --> 00:59:35.880
I'm fine with.

00:59:35.880 --> 00:59:37.100
And AM radio--

00:59:37.100 --> 00:59:39.940
they shave off the top and the
bottom, and it's mono.

00:59:39.940 --> 00:59:41.860
OK, that's fine, I know what's
going to happen.

00:59:41.860 --> 00:59:45.590
But in terms of taking some
sort of encoding algorithm

00:59:45.590 --> 00:59:47.910
that's constantly being
updated-- otherwise, some

00:59:47.910 --> 00:59:50.420
people in this room would
be out of a job--

00:59:50.420 --> 00:59:53.390
I can't work for that because
it's a moving target.

00:59:53.390 --> 00:59:57.170
So my idea is if I make it sound
great, it will survive

00:59:57.170 --> 00:59:58.370
the process better.

00:59:58.370 --> 01:00:00.530
And that, I've actually
found is true.

01:00:00.530 --> 01:00:03.260
Like this Blue Note stuff
sound so amazing and so

01:00:03.260 --> 01:00:07.520
natural that you can start to
hear things get hashy and it's

01:00:07.520 --> 01:00:09.760
a little more annoying and a
little brash, and the panning

01:00:09.760 --> 01:00:10.860
isn't as wide.

01:00:10.860 --> 01:00:13.670
But musically, it's still pretty
awesome, and it's OK.

01:00:13.670 --> 01:00:14.550
And it survives better.

01:00:14.550 --> 01:00:19.240
And strangely, a lot of the
urban music survives better,

01:00:19.240 --> 01:00:21.690
because there's lots of
separation between the

01:00:21.690 --> 01:00:22.610
instruments.

01:00:22.610 --> 01:00:25.360
Things are very discretely
encompassed in terms of their

01:00:25.360 --> 01:00:27.430
frequencies and things
like that.

01:00:27.430 --> 01:00:28.660
They're not sharing
a lot of space.

01:00:28.660 --> 01:00:31.020
You don't have 15 microphones
on a drum kit that are all

01:00:31.020 --> 01:00:32.300
making noise.

01:00:32.300 --> 01:00:34.830
So that actually translates
better.

01:00:34.830 --> 01:00:39.400
And strangely, there is zero hip
hop or R&amp;B that I was able

01:00:39.400 --> 01:00:41.440
to get, other than the
Espreranza Spalding

01:00:41.440 --> 01:00:42.550
record, in high res.

01:00:42.550 --> 01:00:43.230
It doesn't exist.

01:00:43.230 --> 01:00:44.720
CD is as high as it goes.

01:00:44.720 --> 01:00:47.280
They turn in masters that are
44.1-16, because they're

01:00:47.280 --> 01:00:49.450
building it on a laptop.

01:00:49.450 --> 01:00:52.582
And they're actually building
their tracks with MP3s.

01:00:52.582 --> 01:00:53.832
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:00:56.130 --> 01:01:01.520
compressed not in bytes but
making the lowest part of the

01:01:01.520 --> 01:01:02.770
music-- the softest
one-- high.

01:01:05.290 --> 01:01:10.010
So if people start doing
that [INAUDIBLE]

01:01:10.010 --> 01:01:12.728
what's the point in
going to high res?

01:01:12.728 --> 01:01:16.530
ANDREW SCHEPS: Well, I would
argue that even something that

01:01:16.530 --> 01:01:19.480
doesn't have a whole lot of
dynamic range, you will still

01:01:19.480 --> 01:01:24.150
absolutely here the difference
when you have a very lossly

01:01:24.150 --> 01:01:24.870
encoded file.

01:01:24.870 --> 01:01:27.300
You start to destroy things
other than just the dynamic

01:01:27.300 --> 01:01:28.320
range, right?

01:01:28.320 --> 01:01:30.700
There's frequency content,
there's panning content,

01:01:30.700 --> 01:01:32.640
there's the mono versus
stereo content,

01:01:32.640 --> 01:01:33.970
there's depth of field.

01:01:33.970 --> 01:01:36.190
There are all of the cues that
are being taken away, all the

01:01:36.190 --> 01:01:38.700
acoustic cues and reverb tails
and things like that.

01:01:38.700 --> 01:01:40.590
And that will affect it even
if it's super loud.

01:01:40.590 --> 01:01:42.940
I mean, there's this whole thing
called the loudness war,

01:01:42.940 --> 01:01:45.030
which maybe you know about,
but they just like--

01:01:45.030 --> 01:01:47.620
I won that war, OK?

01:01:47.620 --> 01:01:50.160
I mixed "Death Magnetic,"
which was the album that

01:01:50.160 --> 01:01:52.280
everybody said was the poster
child for things

01:01:52.280 --> 01:01:54.560
being way too loud.

01:01:54.560 --> 01:01:55.360
OK, so I won.

01:01:55.360 --> 01:01:57.780
Therefore, the war is over, we
don't have to worry about it.

01:01:57.780 --> 01:01:58.650
[LAUGHTER]

01:01:58.650 --> 01:02:04.940
ANDREW SCHEPS: I spent weeks
reencoding for iTunes and

01:02:04.940 --> 01:02:07.900
Amazon at that time
to make those

01:02:07.900 --> 01:02:10.070
files work lossly encoded.

01:02:10.070 --> 01:02:13.580
So what happens is you start
to get rid of dynamic range

01:02:13.580 --> 01:02:15.740
and things like that, is you
start to break the encoders.

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:17.870
The encoders need some
room to work.

01:02:17.870 --> 01:02:20.370
So I'm making it very difficult
for that to work.

01:02:20.370 --> 01:02:22.745
And one of the things we found
that worked great was turn the

01:02:22.745 --> 01:02:25.920
mix down 0.7 db, period.

01:02:25.920 --> 01:02:27.980
Just let there be headroom
that we never even use,

01:02:27.980 --> 01:02:31.290
because it's brick
wall right there.

01:02:31.290 --> 01:02:35.230
We never get up to that last
0.7, but all of a sudden, all

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:37.620
of the encoders sounded about
100 times better.

01:02:37.620 --> 01:02:43.060
When we got to give them 24-bit
files for the last

01:02:43.060 --> 01:02:44.900
Chili Peppers record-- that was
right at the beginning of

01:02:44.900 --> 01:02:47.790
the mastered for iTunes project
at Apple-- and the big

01:02:47.790 --> 01:02:50.470
crux of that project is give
us 24-bit files instead of

01:02:50.470 --> 01:02:51.690
16-bit files.

01:02:51.690 --> 01:02:53.000
That made a huge difference.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:55.980
So in terms of what you feed
the encoder, it isn't just

01:02:55.980 --> 01:03:00.440
about the source material in
terms of a sonic thing.

01:03:00.440 --> 01:03:03.800
Because I think there are lots
of hardcore and punk albums

01:03:03.800 --> 01:03:06.850
that, from a sonic audio file
point of view, sound terrible.

01:03:06.850 --> 01:03:10.550
But they are so super exciting
that people love those bands

01:03:10.550 --> 01:03:12.140
and they want to
listen to them.

01:03:12.140 --> 01:03:17.640
And if you do a 128 MP3 of that
album, what used to be

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:21.150
hashy and exciting is now just
hashy and noisy, and I think

01:03:21.150 --> 01:03:23.320
there are lots of people who
wouldn't get into the band as

01:03:23.320 --> 01:03:25.760
much as they would even if they
buy it on a cassette,

01:03:25.760 --> 01:03:28.300
which doesn't have anything
above 12k on it, or

01:03:28.300 --> 01:03:28.980
something like that.

01:03:28.980 --> 01:03:32.790
So there are two very different
aesthetic paths you

01:03:32.790 --> 01:03:34.120
can take when you talk
about the music.

01:03:34.120 --> 01:03:36.610
And the problem is, it's
not like with TV.

01:03:36.610 --> 01:03:41.570
Right, with TV, who is going to
argue that a high def set

01:03:41.570 --> 01:03:44.060
looks worse than an SD set?

01:03:44.060 --> 01:03:46.690
Because you see it, and
it's easy to A-B.

01:03:46.690 --> 01:03:48.860
Some people like the artifacts
and you're used

01:03:48.860 --> 01:03:49.600
to things like that.

01:03:49.600 --> 01:03:52.170
And if you have a bad digital
set that pixelates,

01:03:52.170 --> 01:03:53.540
there can be issues.

01:03:53.540 --> 01:03:56.600
And if you look at bad material
on an HD set, it

01:03:56.600 --> 01:03:57.990
looks terrible.

01:03:57.990 --> 01:04:00.420
OK, so all those arguments
are true.

01:04:00.420 --> 01:04:03.650
But let's say you have a
well-captured still image, and

01:04:03.650 --> 01:04:06.180
you show it on these
two different TVs.

01:04:06.180 --> 01:04:08.290
One of them has way more
information about it and it

01:04:08.290 --> 01:04:10.460
just looks a hell of
a lot better, the

01:04:10.460 --> 01:04:11.440
other one does not.

01:04:11.440 --> 01:04:14.530
Whereas with audio, people don't
trust what they hear.

01:04:14.530 --> 01:04:17.270
People think you have to be
trained to like something

01:04:17.270 --> 01:04:19.820
better when you just talk
about audio formats.

01:04:19.820 --> 01:04:21.890
And people believe what
they're told, period.

01:04:21.890 --> 01:04:24.930
I mean, nothing influences your
opinion about things more

01:04:24.930 --> 01:04:27.780
than me telling you how
great it is, right?

01:04:27.780 --> 01:04:30.990
If someone's about to play you
something by a certain band

01:04:30.990 --> 01:04:34.590
and you like them, and they say,
I can't stand this band,

01:04:34.590 --> 01:04:37.400
check it out, you will
not like that band.

01:04:37.400 --> 01:04:39.650
If they say this is my favorite
band in the whole

01:04:39.650 --> 01:04:41.830
world, you're going to try
really, really hard to like

01:04:41.830 --> 01:04:43.210
that band because you
like that person.

01:04:43.210 --> 01:04:46.220
So there's so much that goes
into liking music that has

01:04:46.220 --> 01:04:48.420
nothing to do with any of
this, but it also has

01:04:48.420 --> 01:04:51.750
everything to do with it,
because I really believe that

01:04:51.750 --> 01:04:52.820
there are just thresholds.

01:04:52.820 --> 01:04:55.280
And for every person listening
to a new piece of music,

01:04:55.280 --> 01:04:57.080
there's a threshold of,
am I going to like it?

01:04:57.080 --> 01:04:58.340
Am I not going to like it?

01:04:58.340 --> 01:05:01.710
And the more you can give them
something that sounds true to

01:05:01.710 --> 01:05:05.840
whatever the artist decided
was done, the lower that

01:05:05.840 --> 01:05:07.900
threshold will be, and the
easier it is to connect.

01:05:07.900 --> 01:05:10.890
So regardless, let's listen to
some stuff, unless you want to

01:05:10.890 --> 01:05:11.920
keep talking.

01:05:11.920 --> 01:05:14.320
AUDIENCE: So when did you do
that, the Death Metallic?

01:05:14.320 --> 01:05:16.250
ANDREW SCHEPS: The Metallica
mix? "Death Magnetic"?

01:05:16.250 --> 01:05:17.060
That was--

01:05:17.060 --> 01:05:19.260
I don't know, six years
ago, seven years ago?

01:05:19.260 --> 01:05:20.730
AUDIENCE: What made
you [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:20.730 --> 01:05:22.905
ANDREW SCHEPS: What made
me destroy it?

01:05:22.905 --> 01:05:24.605
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

01:05:24.605 --> 01:05:25.030
ANDREW SCHEPS: OK.

01:05:25.030 --> 01:05:28.210
That is a conversation
that is not--

01:05:28.210 --> 01:05:29.990
I mean, really the only thing
I would say about that is I

01:05:29.990 --> 01:05:32.220
have nothing to say
about that.

01:05:32.220 --> 01:05:35.460
The idea that me as an engineer
could mix a record in

01:05:35.460 --> 01:05:39.110
such a way that was destroyed,
but everybody would be OK with

01:05:39.110 --> 01:05:41.410
it and let it out into the
world is just crazy.

01:05:41.410 --> 01:05:43.760
There is a band involved, there
are producers involved,

01:05:43.760 --> 01:05:45.190
there are plenty of people
involved who

01:05:45.190 --> 01:05:47.280
said, this is awesome.

01:05:47.280 --> 01:05:50.880
Now during the process, whether
or not I made quieter

01:05:50.880 --> 01:05:53.810
mixes to A B,and an let them
hear differences and whatever,

01:05:53.810 --> 01:05:57.170
I may have done, but
